{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638748"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17733"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17733"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10447"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17733"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1456"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5931"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24396"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of persistent dizziness. She describes the sensation as \u0022the room spinning\u0022 and that has not improved. She had flu-like symptoms a week prior to the onset of her current presentation. She denies any hearing loss or tinnitus. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is unremarkable except for a positive head impulse test.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acoustic neuroma","Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo","Labyrinthitis","Meniere\u0027s disease","Vestibular neuritis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with persistent vertigo lasting more than 24 hours without hearing loss, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E. Vestibular neuritis is an inflammation of the vestibular nerve, often following a viral infection, and presents with acute onset of prolonged vertigo and imbalance without auditory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign paroxysmal positional vertigo\u003C/strong\u003E (BPPV) is characterised by brief episodes of vertigo triggered by changes in head position. It is unlikely in this case due to the persistent nature of the vertigo and lack of positional triggers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with episodic vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus. The absence of hearing loss and tinnitus makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabyrinthitis\u003C/strong\u003E involves both the vestibular and cochlear nerves, leading to vertigo and hearing loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcoustic neuroma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with unilateral hearing loss and tinnitus, along with possible vertigo.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vestibular neuritis is characterised by persistent vertigo without hearing loss, often following a viral infection.","Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) presents with brief episodes of vertigo triggered by head movements.","Meniere\u0027s disease is associated with episodic vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus."],"references":["Bae CH, Na HG, Choi YS. Current diagnosis and treatment of vestibular neuritis: a narrative review. J Yeungnam Med Sci. 2022 Apr;39(2):81-88. doi: 10.12701/yujm.2021.01228. Epub 2021 Aug 9. PMID: 34411472; PMCID: PMC8913909.","Manzari L, Graziano D, Tramontano M. The Different Stages of Vestibular Neuritis from the Point of View of the Video Head Impulse Test. Audiol Res. 2020 Aug 24;10(2):31-38. doi: 10.4081/audiores.2020.248. PMID: 33704148; PMCID: PMC7768365.","Smith T, Rider J, Cen S, et al. Vestibular Neuronitis. [Updated 2023 Jul 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549866/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17733"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61881"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T09:53:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T09:53:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10447"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76372"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":nul